## Implementation rules

### Mock-first workflow

Design changes start in the mock workspace. Implement in mock first
(trait signatures, struct definitions), validate with `cargo check`,
regenerate docs with `cargo mock`, then port to real implementation
once the per-crate design stabilises.

### Monomorphisation discipline

- No `dyn Trait`. Every dispatch must be static.
- No `TypeId`, no `std::any`. Type identity is the monomorphised
  function.
- WorkUnits are generic over their `AccessSet`. The `AccessSet` is
  declared as an associated type (`type Access: AccessSetDecl;`).
  The engine composes WUs into fused per-core programs that LLVM
  devirtualises into straight-line code.
- No `Box<dyn Fn(...)>` or `Box<dyn Any>`. All closures are
  monomorphised; all state is strongly typed.
- Generics over const values (fiber width, morsel size) are the
  norm. Runtime-sized values are computed at plan time and stored
  in arvo bitmasks / sparse structures.

### Static composition

- WUs are registered with the scheduler builder at compile time.
- No `inventory::submit!`, no `#[ctor]`, no
  `#[distributed_slice]`. The `no-runtime-registration` lint and
  hook block these tokens outright.
- The `scheduler::Builder` takes a tuple of WU types; composition
  completes at type-level. Plan parameters (fiber width, morsel
  size, core pinning) adapt at plan time; composition does not.
- Consumers extend the engine by adding WUs to their builder tuple,
  not by injecting descriptors into a global registry.

### No runtime spawn

- No `thread::spawn`, `std::thread::spawn`, `tokio::spawn`,
  `async_std::spawn`. Threads are spawned once at pipeline
  construction via a consumer-provided `ThreadPool` implementation.
- Between frames, pool threads park. Wakeup is hybrid: spin 128
  iterations, then park. Predictive parking at sync points:
  <100ns spin, 100ns-10µs `spin_loop`, >10µs park.
- No work-stealing by default. Morsels are assigned deterministically
  at plan time. Consumers who need stealing implement a custom
  `Executor` trait.

### Columns, not tables

Use the canonical vocabulary everywhere in source (comments,
docstrings, type names, field names):

- `pipeline`, `core`, `phase`, `waist`, `trunk`, `fiber`, `branch`,
  `bridge`, `morsel`, `micro-morsel`, `entry`, `record`.

Never use the dead terms in source code: `chain`, `chain_group`,
`partition`, `archetype`, `entity`, `row`, `order`. The vocabulary
lint and reminder hook will catch them. If you find yourself
reaching for one of these words, re-read `mock/DESIGN.md.tmpl`
"Vocabulary" section — there's a canonical term for the concept.

- `Column<T>` holds N records for one field. Columns are independent.
- `Resource<T>` is a single-value shared resource.
- `Virtual<T>` is a computed view.
- No tabular joins. Access is column-scoped; the `AccessSet` declares
  which columns a WU reads and writes.

### Deterministic morsel assignment

- Morsel size is computed from record count, phase width, and the
  consumer's `Strategy` (Hot / Warm / Cold / Precise).
- Assignment is static once computed. The dispatch emitter bakes
  `(fiber_id, morsel_range)` tuples into per-core programs.
- If consumer wants adaptive / work-stealing behaviour, they wire
  an `Executor` that implements stealing semantics. The built-in
  executor does not steal.

### Schedule reuse

- `ExecutionPlan` is computed once per pipeline structure. Frame
  execution reuses it verbatim.
- Plan recompute is triggered only by: new WU composition, record
  count crossing a rebalance threshold, DAG structure change.
- Recompute cost is microseconds on typical DAGs — amortised over
  thousands of frames of reuse.

### Error handling

- WU `execute() -> ()`. The default is abort on failure.
- Consumers who want tolerance wire error columns/virtuals into
  their pipeline. A fiber failure freezes that fiber and poisons
  dependents; independent fibers continue.
- `PipelineResult` reports per-fiber status (Completed / Failed /
  Poisoned).

### Code conventions

- `#![no_std]` in every `lib.rs`.
- No `unwrap()` in non-test code. Plan-time errors are surfaced
  through `PlanResult`; runtime errors use the error column
  pattern.
- Target < 300 LOC per file, max 500 (the `file-size` lint
  enforces).
- Tests alongside source in `#[cfg(test)] mod tests`.
- Doc comments `///` on every public item. The
  `undocumented-type` lint flags types missing from any DESIGN
  doc.
